1
00:00:00,400 --> 00:00:05,648
A six-year-old tips a pile of bricks onto the floor. A hundred shapes, a hundred

2
00:00:05,648 --> 00:00:10,546
colors, no idea what to build. Twenty minutes later the booklet is upside-down, the

3
00:00:10,546 --> 00:00:14,395
build has stalled, and the fun has turned into quiet frustration.

4
00:00:15,595 --> 00:00:22,001
The problem is not the bricks. It is the paper manual. It cannot see what bricks are

5
00:00:22,001 --> 00:00:27,277
on the floor, answer a question, or adapt when a child changes their mind.

6
00:00:28,477 --> 00:00:33,394
Meet BrickBuddy. An AI building companion for six- to eight-year-olds. Show it the

7
00:00:33,394 --> 00:00:39,446
pile, pick a build, then change colors, parts, and instructions by voice or tap — and

8
00:00:39,446 --> 00:00:41,337
the manual stays in sync.

9
00:00:42,537 --> 00:00:48,933
One simple path. Discover, inventory, build, learn, celebrate. Voice or a single tap

10
00:00:48,933 --> 00:00:54,837
does the heavy lifting. Here is the live prototype, end to end.

11
00:00:56,037 --> 00:00:59,435
The home screen gives the child one job: show Buddy the bricks.

12
00:00:59,435 --> 00:01:01,700
Tap Let's Build, and the Discover screen opens.

13
00:01:01,700 --> 00:01:05,382
There's one main action — scan my pile — and two secondary doors.

14
00:01:05,382 --> 00:01:08,780
The product never asks a six-year-old to fill in a text box.

15
00:01:08,780 --> 00:01:11,045
We'll tell Buddy out loud what we have.

16
00:01:11,045 --> 00:01:15,293
A scanning sweep crosses the pile. One row at a time, the inventory pops in.

17
00:01:15,293 --> 00:01:18,975
Sixty-seven bricks across nine shapes, with color and count surfaced like a receipt.

18
00:01:18,975 --> 00:01:22,939
Three matched recommendations slide in — each citing the bricks the kid actually has.

19
00:01:22,939 --> 00:01:24,355
We'll pick the Robot Dog.

20
00:01:24,355 --> 00:01:25,771
Here is the core screen.

21
00:01:25,771 --> 00:01:28,603
On the left, the 3D dog grows brick by brick.

22
00:01:28,603 --> 00:01:30,302
On the right, a paper-textured manual.

23
00:01:30,302 --> 00:01:34,267
The current step on one page, the running list of changes on the other.

24
00:01:34,267 --> 00:01:38,231
Right now the build is red. Watch the manual when the child changes it.

25
00:01:38,231 --> 00:01:39,930
The child says: make it blue.

26
00:01:39,930 --> 00:01:43,045
The 3D dog changes first. Then the manual changes with it.

27
00:01:43,045 --> 00:01:44,745
Step text. Piece counts. Color swatches.

28
00:01:44,745 --> 00:01:47,860
On the right page, Buddy stamps the edit: red to blue.

29
00:01:47,860 --> 00:01:50,125
That is the thing paper can never do.

30
00:01:50,125 --> 00:01:50,975
Voice isn't all-or-nothing.

31
00:01:50,975 --> 00:01:53,807
Make the head purple — and only the head changes.

32
00:01:53,807 --> 00:01:56,355
Body, legs, and tail stay exactly as they were.

33
00:01:56,355 --> 00:01:58,338
For precision, pointing is faster than talking.

34
00:01:58,338 --> 00:02:01,169
Tap the orange button, pick a brick, choose a swatch.

35
00:02:01,169 --> 00:02:04,284
BrickBuddy updates that single piece, and the manual logs the edit.

36
00:02:04,284 --> 00:02:06,550
The same engine handles preset structural changes too.

37
00:02:06,550 --> 00:02:07,399
Say: add wings.

38
00:02:07,399 --> 00:02:11,930
BrickBuddy adds a final step to the manual, and the 3D model grows the new parts.

39
00:02:11,930 --> 00:02:14,479
After building, the session pivots from making to learning.

40
00:02:14,479 --> 00:02:18,444
BrickBuddy turns the model into a lesson — stability, levers, sound, symmetry, and measurement.

41
00:02:18,444 --> 00:02:20,992
All tied to the pieces the child just placed.

42
00:02:20,992 --> 00:02:22,975
A two-question quiz closes the learning stage.

43
00:02:22,975 --> 00:02:26,090
Right answers unlock an achievement. Wrong answers bring a friendlier explanation.

44
00:02:26,090 --> 00:02:27,222
Every session ends here.

45
00:02:27,222 --> 00:02:32,037
Confetti, a rotating 3D trophy, a build report, and a printable certificate to put on the fridge.

46
00:02:44,437 --> 00:02:49,857
Three things make this prototype practical. First, one shared engine keeps the model

47
00:02:49,857 --> 00:02:55,277
and manual in sync. Second, brick data is declarative — inventory, steps, and

48
00:02:55,277 --> 00:03:01,948
rendering all read from the same source. Third, it runs as a single web page on

49
00:03:01,948 --> 00:03:05,701
Cloudflare's edge. No install, no app store, no sign-up.

50
00:03:06,901 --> 00:03:14,327
BrickBuddy is a CMAA5043 final project by Yusong Huang and Jiayi Huang. Yusong led the

51
00:03:14,327 --> 00:03:19,772
implementation: every screen, the 3D pipeline, the mutation engine, and the

52
00:03:19,772 --> 00:03:26,208
deployment. Jiayi led the original concept, the user research with children, and the

53
00:03:26,208 --> 00:03:27,198
demo materials.

54
00:03:28,398 --> 00:03:34,404
The prototype is live on Cloudflare's edge. Scan the code, try it in any browser, and

55
00:03:34,404 --> 00:03:38,158
come find us at the CMA exhibition. Thanks for watching.

